Introduction

The objective is to analyze the effectiveness of executing a dollar-cost averaging strategy on the L1 cryptocurrency asset Ethereum (ETH). The analyses will look at implementing a DCA stratgey over daily, weekly, and monthly intervals over a span of 6 years. I will also determine if this strategy can potentially reduce the impact of volatility ans increase overal returns. The project will use historical data from 2015-2022.

Experiment setting

For the sake of this project we will use the median income of a full time employee in the United States as of 2022. The data source used for this analysis was an article from The balance citing data from the Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS). Which states the median income to be at $54,132.

Based on this information the amount of wage per week is $1,041 and $4,511 per month not taking into account bills we will allocate 10% of income to the DCA stratgey.

Our budget will 451 USD per month, we will evaluate investment strategies using this budget based on different timeframes. The timeframes will conist of a single investment at the beginning of each month, week, and day.

Dispersed the investment schedule will be as follows Monthly = 12 investments of 451 usd per investment Weekly = 4 investments per month for a total of 52 of $112.5 per investment Daily = 28,30,or 31 investments of a total of 365 investments of 16.10, 15.03, 14.54 usd

# Define a function to display the plot with a scrolling area
@interact
def show_pairplot(i=(0, len(df.columns) - 1)):
    pair = np.array(np.meshgrid(df.columns, df.columns)).T.reshape(-1, 2)
    selected = pair[i*4:(i+1)*4]
    plt.clf()
    for x, y in selected:
        sns.scatterplot(x=x, y=y, data=df)
    plt.show()

Using Log to check the effects of volume on accumulation

We see that regardless of vol we get a power law L shaped graph, when means that this strategy generally does well with accumulation. But when we look at the amount of accumulation per interval we can see that volume does have a significant effect on accumulation. From the data, we can conclude that in a volatile asset it is better to distribute capital in chunks consistently, in order to mitigate volume associate risk the most.

In [255]:
from scipy.stats import spearmanr

# Load your data into the DataFrame named 'df'

# Extract the columns that you want to calculate the Spearman correlation coefficient for
x = df['Volume']
y = df['ETH_bought_monthly']

# Calculate the Spearman correlation coefficient
coefficient, p_value = spearmanr(x, y)

print("The Spearman correlation coefficient is:", coefficient)
print("The p-value is:", p_value)

# Create a scatter plot with a regression line
sns.regplot(x=x, y=y, ci=None)

# Show the plot
plt.show()

The Spearman correlation coefficient is: -0.7326540426431455
The p-value is: 0.0
  • Volume is needed to drive price action but it negatively affects accumulation
  • From initial analyses its better to maximize the amount invested in order to maximize accumulation and mitigate the risk of volume.

Calculate ROI

In [285]:
# Function to calculate ROI
def calculate_roi(row):
    return (row['monthly_value'] - row['ETH_sum_monthly']) / row['ETH_sum_monthly'] * 100

# Apply the function to the DataFrame
df['monthly_ROI'] = df.apply(calculate_roi, axis=1)

Conclusions

  • Investing 10% of the average full-time employee salary in the US in the ETH through the DCA strategy can change one's life completely.
  • While any timeframe generally works, there is a significant difference in how much accumulation occurs and how exposed you are to volatility. This may be asset related but the longer the timeframe of disbursement the more effective the strategy
  • It was determined that the Return of investment (ROI) after 5 years of investment exceeds 2000% based on the unrealized returns on the last day of purchases in each time frame (daily, weekly, monthly).
